title: Manual
text: See Installation & Quick Start.

title: Manual
text: input ggoncoplot data.frame/data.table/tibble 1 row per mutation cohort columns describing following: Gene Symbol Sample Identifier (optional) mutation type (optional) tooltip (character string: show mouse hover particular mutation) columns can order, named anything. define mapping input dataset columns required features call ggoncoplot.

title: Manual
text: tidyTCGA package provides public tabular cancer datasets. ggoncoplot flexible input data; can use MAF files tabular mutation-level datasets specifying columns sample identifiers gene names.

title: Manual
code: # TCGA GBM dataset from TCGAmuations package gbm_csv <- system.file(package='ggoncoplot', "testdata/GBM_tcgamutations_mc3_maf.csv.gz") gbm_df <- read.csv(file = gbm_csv, header=TRUE)  gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode'   )

title: Manual
text: Colour mutation specifying col_mutation_type
code: # TCGA GBM dataset from TCGAmuations package gbm_csv <- system.file(package='ggoncoplot', "testdata/GBM_tcgamutations_mc3_maf.csv.gz") gbm_df <- read.csv(file = gbm_csv, header=TRUE)  gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification'   ) #>  #> ── Identify Class ── #>  #> ℹ Found 7 unique mutation types in input set #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid PAVE terms #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid SO terms #> ℹ 7/7 mutation types were valid MAF terms #> ✔ Mutation Types are described using valid MAF terms ... using MAF palete

title: Manual
text: Show 4 frequently mutated genes using topn argument
code: gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',      topn = 4   ) #>  #> ── Identify Class ── #>  #> ℹ Found 7 unique mutation types in input set #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid PAVE terms #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid SO terms #> ℹ 7/7 mutation types were valid MAF terms #> ✔ Mutation Types are described using valid MAF terms ... using MAF palete

title: Manual
text: Use genes_to_ignore argument filter specific genes, TTN MUC16. can use packages like somaticflags get lists genes might want filter .
code: gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',      topn = 10,     genes_to_ignore = c("TTN", "MUC16")   ) #>  #> ── Identify Class ── #>  #> ℹ Found 9 unique mutation types in input set #> ℹ 0/9 mutation types were valid PAVE terms #> ℹ 0/9 mutation types were valid SO terms #> ℹ 9/9 mutation types were valid MAF terms #> ✔ Mutation Types are described using valid MAF terms ... using MAF palete

title: Manual
text: lets show TP53 TERT
code: gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',      genes_to_include = c('TP53', 'TERT'),   ) #>  #> ── Identify Class ── #>  #> ℹ Found 6 unique mutation types in input set #> ℹ 0/6 mutation types were valid PAVE terms #> ℹ 0/6 mutation types were valid SO terms #> ℹ 6/6 mutation types were valid MAF terms #> ✔ Mutation Types are described using valid MAF terms ... using MAF palete

title: Manual
text: show_all_samples argument add samples don’t mutations selected genes plot. Note supply metadata table, default samples lacking mutations still shown. can include samples setting metadata_require_mutations = FALSE isn’t recommended unless ’re sure sample truly mutations dataframe.
code: gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',      show_all_samples = TRUE   ) #>  #> ── Identify Class ── #>  #> ℹ Found 7 unique mutation types in input set #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid PAVE terms #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid SO terms #> ℹ 7/7 mutation types were valid MAF terms #> ✔ Mutation Types are described using valid MAF terms ... using MAF palete

title: Manual
text:
Use col_tooltip argument indicate column input dataframe used custom tooltip. Note tooltips html, want insert break, just paste
. Similarly, want make text tooltip bold, try "text_to_bold<\b>". Note single sample multiple mutations gene, represented one tile oncoplot, tooltip mutation shown (newline delimited).
code: # Add a tooltip column to data.frame gbm_df[["tooltip"]] <- with(gbm_df, paste0(Chromosome, ":", Start_Position, " ", Reference_Allele, ">", Tumor_Seq_Allele2))  # Generate oncoplot gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',      col_tooltip = 'tooltip' # We'll specify a custom tooltip based on our new 'tooltip' column   ) #>  #> ── Identify Class ── #>  #> ℹ Found 7 unique mutation types in input set #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid PAVE terms #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid SO terms #> ℹ 7/7 mutation types were valid MAF terms #> ✔ Mutation Types are described using valid MAF terms ... using MAF palete

title: Manual
text: can also add pathway information oncoplot supplying simple 2-column data.frame. Currently default order pathways genes plot based order appearnce pathway data.frame. Future versions ggoncoplot support data-based sorting. genes missing oncoplot displayed ‘’ pathway bottom plot.
code: path_pathways <- system.file("testdata/GBM_tcgamutations_mc3.pathways.csv", package = "ggoncoplot") pathways_df <- read.csv(path_pathways)  gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',      pathway = pathways_df   ) #> Found pathway column: Pathway #> Warning: 7 unknown levels in `f`: Cytoskeleton structure, Nuclear envelope structure, #> Muscle structure, Endocytosis, Extracellular matrix, Ciliary function, and #> Neurotransmitter release #>  #> ── Identify Class ── #>  #> ℹ Found 7 unique mutation types in input set #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid PAVE terms #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid SO terms #> ℹ 7/7 mutation types were valid MAF terms #> ✔ Mutation Types are described using valid MAF terms ... using MAF palete

title: Manual
text: many samples mutations Gene (optionally coloured mutation type)
code: gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',      draw_gene_barplot = TRUE   ) #>  #> ── Identify Class ── #>  #> ℹ Found 7 unique mutation types in input set #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid PAVE terms #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid SO terms #> ℹ 7/7 mutation types were valid MAF terms #> ✔ Mutation Types are described using valid MAF terms ... using MAF palete

title: Manual
text: can use set draw_tmb_barplot = TRUE plot total number mutations (total mutational burden) sample. datasets, presence one hypermutator makes hard see less extreme trends, defualt mutational burden plotted log10 scale. can changed setting log10_transform_tmb = FALSE
code: gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',     draw_tmb_barplot = TRUE,      #log10_transform_tmb = FALSE   ) #>  #> ── Identify Class ── #>  #> ℹ Found 7 unique mutation types in input set #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid PAVE terms #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid SO terms #> ℹ 7/7 mutation types were valid MAF terms #> ✔ Mutation Types are described using valid MAF terms ... using MAF palete #> ! TMB plot: Ignoring `col_mutation_type` since `log10_transform = TRUE`. #> This is because you cannot accurately plot stacked bars on a logarithmic scale

what: Add both TMB and Gene Barplots
title: Manual
text: Usually, ’ll want draw margin plots (tmb + gene).
code: gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',     draw_tmb_barplot = TRUE,      draw_gene = TRUE     # log10_transform_tmb = FALSE   ) #>  #> ── Identify Class ── #>  #> ℹ Found 7 unique mutation types in input set #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid PAVE terms #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid SO terms #> ℹ 7/7 mutation types were valid MAF terms #> ✔ Mutation Types are described using valid MAF terms ... using MAF palete #> ! text: default, clicking tile oncoplot copy sample ID clipboard. can customised using copy argument. example can choose copy tooltip gene instead.
code: gbm_df |>   ggoncoplot(    col_genes = "Hugo_Symbol",    col_samples = "Tumor_Sample_Barcode",    col_mutation_type = "Variant_Classification",    copy = 'gene' # see ?ggoncoplot for other valid values   ) #>  #> ── Identify Class ── #>  #> ℹ Found 7 unique mutation types in input set #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid PAVE terms #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid SO terms #> ℹ 7/7 mutation types were valid MAF terms #> ✔ Mutation Types are described using valid MAF terms ... using MAF palete

title: Manual
text: Want control look oncoplot? ggoncoplot takes options argument help control visual parameters. See ?ggoncoplot_options full list parameters.
code: gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     # Data     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',      draw_tmb_barplot = TRUE,      draw_gene_barplot = TRUE,          #pathway = pathways_df,     metadata = gbm_clinical_df,      cols_to_plot_metadata = c('gender', 'histological_type', 'prior_glioma', 'tumor_tissue_site'),          # Customise Visual Options     options = ggoncoplot_options(              # Interactive Plot Options       interactive_svg_width = 12,       interactive_svg_height = 6,        # Relative the ratio of marginal plot size to main tile plot (% of total plot height/width)       plotsize_gene_rel_width = 40, # Genebar plot takes 50% of plot width       plotsize_tmb_rel_height = 30,       plotsize_metadata_rel_height = 15,          # Axis Titles       xlab_title = "Glioblastoma Samples",       ylab_title = "Top 10 mutated genes",          # Fontsizes       fontsize_xlab = 40,       fontsize_ylab = 40,       fontsize_genes = 16,       fontsize_samples = 12,       fontsize_count = 14,       fontsize_tmb_title = 14,       fontsize_tmb_axis = 11,       fontsize_pathway = 16,          # Customise Tiles       tile_height = 1,       tile_width = 1,       colour_backround = "white",       colour_mutation_type_unspecified = "grey10",          # Show different elements       show_sample_ids = FALSE,       show_ylab_title = FALSE,       show_xlab_title = FALSE,       show_ylab_title_tmb = FALSE,       show_axis_gene = TRUE,       show_axis_tmb = TRUE,          # Gene Barplot Specific Options       show_genebar_labels = TRUE,       genebar_label_padding = 0.1,       genebar_only_pad_when_labels_shown = TRUE,       genebar_label_nudge = 3,       genebar_label_round = 0,        # Transformation and label scales       log10_transform_tmb = TRUE,       scientific_tmb = FALSE,          # Pathway Faceting Colours / Text       colour_pathway_text = "black",       colour_pathway_bg = "white",       colour_pathway_outline = "black",       pathway_text_angle = 0,          # Legend number of columns       ggoncoplot_guide_ncol = 1     ) ) #> ℹ 2 samples with metadata have no mutations. title: Manual
text: building oncoplot interactive=FALSE result patchwork object. lets customise plot standard patchwork styling. example adding title plot_annotation() applying theme subplots (tilegraph & gene barplot) & theme(...).
code: library(patchwork)  library(ggplot2)   # Create oncoplot patchwork oncoplot_patchwork <- gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',     draw_gene_barplot = TRUE,     interactive = FALSE   )  # Customise the theme oncoplot_patchwork +   plot_annotation(title = 'My Glioblastoma Oncoplot') &    theme(text = element_text('mono', face = "bold"))

code: gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',      interactive = FALSE   ) #>  #> ── Identify Class ── #>  #> ℹ Found 7 unique mutation types in input set #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid PAVE terms #> ℹ 0/7 mutation types were valid SO terms #> ℹ 7/7 mutation types were valid MAF terms #> ✔ Mutation Types are described using valid MAF terms ... using MAF palete

title: Manual
text: ggoncoplot outputs can combined packages create interactive multiplots. show co-explore mutation oncoplots, expression t-SNE’s & methylation UMAPs.

what: Install additional packages required to generate interactive multiplots
title: Manual
text: following example uses additional packages: express creating expression plots patchwork combining oncoplot, expression methylation plots single graphic ggiraph making combined plot interactive somaticflags excluding genes commonly mutated somatic tissues oncoplot. install packages run:

title: Manual
text: create oncoplot can interactively coexplored visualisations, set interactive = FALSE ggoncoplot returns ggplot object instead ggiraph. express package visualises TCGA methylation expression data (UMAPs t-SNEs. can use patchwork compose plots single visualisation make entire group interactive data linked across plots.
code: # Load required libraries library(express) # For Creating Expression Plots library(patchwork) # For combining oncoplot and expression plots library(ggiraph) # For making combined plot interactive library(somaticflags) # For excluding genes commonly mutated in somatic tissues  ## Create a Breast Cancer Oncoplot brca_df <- read.csv(system.file("testdata/BRCA_tcgamutations_mc3.csv.gz", package = "ggoncoplot"))  brca_clinical <- read.csv(system.file("testdata/BRCA_tcgamutations_mc3_clinical.csv.gz", package = "ggoncoplot"))  ggoncoplot <- brca_df |>   ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Gene',     col_samples = 'Sample',     col_mutation_type = 'MutationType',     topn = 10,      genes_to_ignore = somaticflags,     metadata = brca_clinical,     metadata_palette =       list(         Progesterone = c("Indeterminate" = "gray80", "Negative" = "black", "Positive" = "#DF536B", "[Not Evaluated]" = "grey90"),         Estrogen = c("Indeterminate" = "gray80", "Negative" = "black", "Positive" = "#DF536B", "[Not Evaluated]" = "grey90"),         HER2 = c("Indeterminate" = "gray80", Equivocal =  "grey80", "Negative" = "black", "Positive" = "#DF536B", "[Not Evaluated]" = "grey90"),         Classification = c("Ambiguous" = "gray80", "Triple Negative" = "black", "Not Triple Negative" = "#ff0000")         ),     options = ggoncoplot_options(       show_genebar_labels = TRUE,        plotsize_metadata_rel_height = 40,        plotsize_tmb_rel_height = 10,        genebar_label_nudge = 20,        fontsize_genes = 11,       fontsize_metadata_text = 11,       show_legend = FALSE     ),     interactive = FALSE,     verbose=FALSE   )   ## Create a gene expression t-SNE describing the same BRCA cohort tsne_expression <- express_precomputed("BRCA", datatype = "expression", interactive = FALSE)  ## Create a methylation UMAP describing the same BRCA cohort umap_methylation <- express_precomputed("BRCA", datatype = "methylation", interactive = FALSE)  ## Combine plots with patchwork combined_plots <- (tsne_expression + umap_methylation) / ggoncoplot  + plot_layout(heights = c(3.5, 6.5))  # View the interactive version with ggiraph interactive_multiplot <- girafe(ggobj = combined_plots, height_svg = 6, width_svg = 9)  # Add some settings to choose how to make combined plots interactive interactive_multiplot <- girafe_options(x = interactive_multiplot,     opts_selection(type = "multiple", only_shiny = FALSE, css = "opacity: 1"),     opts_selection_inv(css = "opacity: 0.12")     )  interactive_multiplot

title: Manual
text: ggoncoplot interactive = FALSE returns ggplot object aesthetics required ggiraph interactivity baked (case, e.g. ‘data_id’ defined values col_sample). long packages also produce data_id aesthetic matched values (using ggiraph package) + optionally tooltip & onclick aesthetics, can use patchwork combine plots.

title: Manual
text: current version ggoncoplot, download button interactive plot downloads low-resolution image. recommend following alternatives high-quality plots suitable scientific publications: save non-interactive plot 300 dpi PNG, PDF, SVG, use ggsaves function ggsaves. save interactive plot HTML, SVG, PDF formats (high-resolution PNGs can derived), use ggisaves function ggsaves. Alternatives: - Export non-interactive graph format using preferred export method R plots (e.g., RStudio GUI, ggplot2::ggsave()). - Export interactive graph format using preferred export method R HTML widgets (e.g., RStudio GUI htmlwidgets::saveWidget()).

title: Sorting Algorithm
text: common approach sorting oncoplot hierarchical sort, follows steps:

what: Step 1: Identify Sort Order for Y Axis
title: Sorting Algorithm
text: Determine genes mutated greatest proportion samples (multi-hits gene don’t count towards quantification recurrence). Identify top N genes (default 10) based recurrent mutations across samples. Rank genes based degree recurrence. ranking determines sort order Y axis.

what: Step 2: Identify Sort Order for X Axis
title: Sorting Algorithm
text: X axis sorted based Y axis.

previous_headings: How are oncoplot axes sorted? > Step 2: Identify Sort Order for X Axis
title: Sorting Algorithm
text: Rank sample samples mutations recurrently mutated gene appear furthest left oncoplot. followed samples mutations second recurrently mutated gene, . Within group samples mutations specific gene, want sort based whether next mutated gene mutated, continue process hierarchically.

previous_headings: How are oncoplot axes sorted? > Step 2: Identify Sort Order for X Axis
title: Sorting Algorithm
text: X axis hierarchical sort achieved using base-2 scoring system. display top 5 recurrently mutated genes Y axis, allocate weighting gene based ranking order recurrence: recurrent gene weight 2(5−1)=162^{(5-1)} = 16. second recurrent gene weight 2(4−1)=82^{(4-1)} = 8. . sample’s X axis sorting rank calculated summing weights genes mutated sample.

title: Easily Create Interactive Oncoplots
text: Oncoplots highly effective visualising mutation data cancer cohorts challenging generate major R plotting systems (base, lattice, ggplot2) due algorithmic graphical complexity. Simplifying process generating oncoplots make accessible researchers. Existing packages including ComplexHeatmap, maftools, genVisR make static oncoplots easier create, still significant unmet need user-friendly method creating oncoplots following features: Interactive plots: Customizable tooltips, cross-selection samples across different plots, auto-copying sample identifiers click. enables exploration multiomic datasets. Support tidy datasets: Compatibility tidy, tabular mutation-level formats cancer cohort datasets typically stored . greatly improves range datasets can quickly easily visualised oncoplot since genomic data Mutation Annotation Format (MAF) files relational databases usually follow structure. Auto-colouring: Automatic selection accessible colour palettes datasets consequence annotations aligned standard variant effect dictionaries including Prediction Annotation Variant Effects (PAVE), Sequence Ontology () MAF Variant Classifications. Versatility: ability visualize entities gene mutations, noncoding features (e.g., promoter enhancer mutations) non-genomic entities (e.g., microbial presence microbiome datasets). developed ggoncoplot first R package address challenges together. Examples key features available ggoncoplot manual. full comparison ggoncoplot features similar tools available

title: Easily Create Interactive Oncoplots
text: ggOncoplot can produce default, interactive oncoplot even largest TCGA cancer cohort (Breast Cancer - BRCA) contains 1026 samples 0.81 seconds (Macbook Pro; M3 Pro Chip; 18GB ram). Since number mutations genomic dataset change number tiles rendered final oncoplot, 10x increase variant number (1,350,300) takes 1.3x longer plot. Code used benchmarking shown .
code: library(microbenchmark) # install.packages("microbenchmark")  # Setup Data data <- read.csv(system.file("testdata/BRCA_tcgamutations_mc3.csv.gz", package = "ggoncoplot"))  # Increase variant count by 10x data_10x <- do.call("rbind", replicate(n = 10, data, simplify = FALSE))  # Benchmark microbenchmark(   interactive = print(ggoncoplot(data, col_samples = "Sample", col_genes = "Gene", col_mutation_type = "MutationType", verbose = FALSE)),    interactive_10x = print(ggoncoplot(data_10x, col_samples = "Sample", col_genes = "Gene", col_mutation_type = "MutationType", verbose = FALSE)),   static = print(ggoncoplot(data, col_samples = "Sample", col_genes = "Gene", col_mutation_type = "MutationType", verbose = FALSE, interactive = FALSE)),   static_10x = print(ggoncoplot(data_10x, col_samples = "Sample", col_genes = "Gene", col_mutation_type = "MutationType", verbose = FALSE, interactive = FALSE)),   times = 18 )

title: Easily Create Interactive Oncoplots
text: Responsiveness interactive graphics may slow number tiles oncoplot (samples x genes increases) especially tooltips contain large amounts information. MacBook Pro (M3 Pro chip 18GB memory) largest TCGA dataset (BRCA) including 1026 samples can rendered sample IDs tooltip noticeable delay tooltip responsiveness.

title: ggoncoplot — ggoncoplot
code: ggoncoplot(   data,   col_genes,   col_samples,   col_mutation_type = NULL,   genes_to_include = NULL,   genes_to_ignore = NULL,   col_tooltip = col_samples,   topn = 10,   return_extra_genes_if_tied = FALSE,   draw_gene_barplot = FALSE,   draw_tmb_barplot = FALSE,   copy = c("sample", "gene", "tooltip", "mutation_type", "nothing"),   palette = NULL,   metadata = NULL,   metadata_palette = NULL,   col_samples_metadata = col_samples,   cols_to_plot_metadata = NULL,   metadata_require_mutations = TRUE,   pathway = NULL,   col_genes_pathway = col_genes,   show_all_samples = FALSE,   total_samples = c("any_mutations", "all", "oncoplot"),   sample_order = NULL,   metadata_sort_cols = NULL,   metadata_sort_desc = TRUE,   metadata_sort_by = "frequency",   interactive = TRUE,   options = ggoncoplot_options(),   verbose = TRUE )

title: ggoncoplot — ggoncoplot
text: data data oncoplot. data.frame 1 row per mutation cohort. Must contain columns describing gene_symbols sample_identifiers (data.frame) col_genes name data column containing gene names/symbols (string) col_samples name data column containing sample identifiers (string) col_mutation_type name data column describing mutation types (string, optional) genes_to_include specific genes include oncoplot (character, optional) genes_to_ignore names genes ignored (character, optional) col_tooltip name data column containing whatever information want display (string, defaults col_samples) topn many top genes visualize. Ignored genes_to_include supplied (number, default 10) return_extra_genes_if_tied instead strictly returning topn genes, case ties (multiple genes mutated exact number samples, complicating selection top n genes), return tied genes (potentially topn). FALSE, return strictly topn genes, breaking ties based order appearance dataset (flag, default FALSE) draw_gene_barplot add barplot describing number samples gene mutated (right side) (flag, default FALSE) draw_tmb_barplot add barplot describing total number mutations sample (main plot). single gene mutated multiple times, mutations counted towards total (flag, default FALSE) copy value copy clipboard oncoplot tile clicked (string, one 'sample', 'gene', 'tooltip', 'mutation_type', 'nothing', default 'sample') palette named vector mapping possible mutation types (vector names) colors (vector values, optional) metadata dataframe describing sample level metadata. One column must contain unique sample identifiers. columns can describe numeric / categorical metadata (data.frame, optional) metadata_palette list named vectors. List names correspond metadata column names (categorical ). Vector names levels columns. Vector values colors, vector names used map values data color. (optional) col_samples_metadata column metadata data.frame describes sample identifiers (string, defaults col_samples) cols_to_plot_metadata names columns metadata plotted (character, optional) metadata_require_mutations filter samples metadata lacking mutations data (flag, default TRUE) pathway two column dataframe describing pathway. column containing gene names name col_gene (data.frame, optional) col_genes_pathway column pathway data.frame describes gene names (string, defaults col_genes) show_all_samples show samples oncoplot, even mutations selected genes. Samples described metadata mutations still filtered default, can show setting metadata_require_mutations = FALSE (flag, default FALSE) total_samples Strategy calculating total number samples. value used compute proportion mutation recurrence displayed tooltip hovering gene barplot, text annotation ggoncoplot_options(show_genebar_labels = TRUE) set TRUE. Possible values: any_mutations: samples data (mutation dataset), irrespective whether oncoplot . oncoplot: samples present oncoplot. : samples either data metadata. sample_order sample IDs order shown oncoplot (left right). Overrides gene-based auto-ranking. (character vector). metadata_sort_cols character vector metadata columns sort . NULL default typical gene-based sort unless sample_order specified. metadata_sort_desc Logical scalar vector indicating whether rank column descending order. single value supplied recycled columns. metadata_sort_by Character vector specifying rank non-numeric column. Valid values include "alphabetical" "frequency". single value supplied recycled columns. numeric columns, sort_by ignored ranking always based numeric order. interactive plot interactive (boolean, default TRUE) options list additional visual parameters created calling ggoncoplot_options(). See ggoncoplot_options details. verbose verbose mode (flag, default TRUE)

Ignored unless show_sample_ids set true (number) fontsize_legend_title fontsize legend titles  (number) fontsize_legend_text fontsize legend text (number) tile_height proportion available vertical space tile take (0-1) (number) tile_width proportion available horizontal space tile take (0-1) (number) copy value copy clipboard oncoplot tile clicked (string, one 'sample', 'gene', 'tooltip', 'mutation_type', 'nothing', default 'sample') colour_backround colour used background non-mutated tiles (string) colour_mutation_type_unspecified colour mutations oncoplot margin plots col_mutation_type supplied (string) fontsize_pathway fontsize y axis strip text describing gene pathways (number) colour_pathway_text colour text describing pathways (string) colour_pathway_bg background fill colour pathway strips (string) colour_pathway_outline outline colour pathway strips (string) pathway_text_angle angle pathway text label (typically 0 90 degrees) (number) legend_title name legend title (string) show_legend_titles show legend titles (flag) ggoncoplot_guide_ncol many columns use describing oncoplot legend (number) legend_key_size width legend key block (number) margin_t, margin_r, margin_b, margin_l margin top, right, bottom, left side plot. default, unit 'cm' can changed setting margin_unit value ggplot2::margin() understand (number) margin_unit Unit margin specification. default 'cm' can changed setting margin_unit value ggplot2::margin() understand (string) mutation_type_supplied user supply mutation_type column? , turn legend. prettify_legend_values legend values prettified human-readable forms (e.g. converting 'my_title' 'Title'). title: Generate score based on genes — score_based_on_gene_rank
code: if (FALSE) { # \dontrun{ # First set of genes has a high rank since both BRCA2 and EGFR are mutated score_based_on_gene_rank(c("TERT", "EGFR", "PTEN", "BRCA2"), c("EGFR", "BRCA2"), gene_rank = 1:2)  # If EGFR is mutated without BRCA2, we get a lower score score_based_on_gene_rank(c("TERT", "EGFR", "PTEN", "IDH1"), c("EGFR", "BRCA2"), gene_rank = 1:2)  # If BRCA2 is mutated without EGFR, # we get a score lower than BRCA2+EGFR but higher than EGFR alone due to higher gene_rank of BRCA2 score_based_on_gene_rank(c("TERT", "IDH1", "PTEN", "BRCA2"), c("EGFR", "BRCA2"), gene_rank = 1:2) } # }
